SIMPLE: swallow
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swallow
<hw>Swal"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>swalowe</ets>, AS. <ets>swalewe</ets>, <ets>swealwe</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>zwaluw</ets>, OHG. <ets>swalawa</ets>, G. <ets>schwalbe</ets>,
Icel. & Sw. <ets>svala</ets>, Dan. <ets>svale</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of passerine birds
of the family <fam>Hirundinidae</fam>, especially one of those species
in which the tail is deeply forked. They have long, pointed wings, and
are noted for the swiftness and gracefulness of their flight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The most common North American species are the barn
swallow (see under <er>Barn</er>), the cliff, or eaves, swallow (see
under <er>Cliff</er>), the white-bellied, or tree, swallow
(<spn>Tachycineta bicolor</spn>), and the bank swallow (see under
<er>Bank</er>). The common European swallow (<spn>Chelidon
rustica</spn>), and the window swallow, or martin (<spn>Chelidon
urbica</spn>), are familiar species.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of
swifts which resemble the true swallows in form and habits, as the
common American chimney swallow, or swift.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The aperture in a block through
which the rope reeves.</def> <rj><au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Swallow plover</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one
of several species of fork-tailed ploverlike birds of the genus
<gen>Glareola</gen>, as <spn>Glareola orientalis</spn> of India; a
pratincole.</cd> -- <col><b>Swallow shrike</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>any one of several species of East Indian and Asiatic birds of the
family <fam>Artamiidae</fam>, allied to the shrikes but similar to
swallows in appearance and habits. The ashy swallow shrike (<spn>Artamus
fuscus</spn>) is common in India.</cd> -- <col><b>Swallow
warbler</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any one of numerous species of
East Indian and Australian singing birds of the genus
<gen>Dicaeum</gen>. They are allied to the honeysuckers.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swallow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swallow
<hw>Swal"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Swallowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Swallowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>swolewen</ets>, <ets>swolwen</ets>, <ets>swolhen</ets>, AS.
<ets>swelgan</ets>; akin to D. <ets>zwelgen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>swelahan</ets>, <ets>swelgan</ets>, G. <ets>schwelgen</ets> to
feast, to revel, Icel. <ets>svelgia</ets> to swallow, SW.
<ets>sv⟦aum⟧lja</ets>, Dan. <ets>svaelge</ets>. Cf. <er>Groundsel</er> a
plant.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take into the stomach; to receive
through the gullet, or esophagus, into the stomach; <as>as, to
<ex>swallow</ex> food or drink</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As if I had <qex>swallowed</qex> snowballs for pills.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw into an abyss or gulf; to ingulf; to absorb
-- usually followed by <xex>up</xex>.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The earth opened her mouth, and <qex>swallowed</qex> them up, and
their houses.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xvi. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To receive or embrace, as opinions or belief,
without examination or scruple; to receive implicitly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though that story . . . be not so readily
<qex>swallowed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To engross; to appropriate; -- usually with
<xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Homer excels . . . in this, that he <qex>swallowed</qex> up the
honor of those who succeeded him.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To occupy; to take up; to employ.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The necessary provision of the life <qex>swallows</qex> the
greatest part of their time.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To seize and waste; to exhaust; to
consume.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Corruption <qex>swallowed</qex> what the liberal hand⟦br⟧
Of bounty scattered.</q> <rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To retract; to recant; <as>as, to <ex>swallow</ex>
one's opinions</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Swallowed</xex> his vows
whole.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To put up with; to bear patiently or without
retaliation; <as>as, to <ex>swallow</ex> an affront or
insult</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To absorb; imbibe; ingulf; engross; consume. See
<er>Absorb</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swallow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swallow
<hw>Swal"low</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To perform the act of
swallowing; <as>as, his cold is so severe he is unable to
<ex>swallow</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swallow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Swallow
<hw>Swal"low</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
swallowing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The gullet, or esophagus; the throat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Taste; relish; inclination; liking.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have no <qex>swallow</qex> for it.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Capacity for swallowing; voracity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There being nothing too gross for the <qex>swallow</qex> of
political rancor.</q> <rj><qau>Prof. Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>As much as is, or can be, swallowed at once; <as>as,
a <ex>swallow</ex> of water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>That which ingulfs; a whirlpool.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Fabyan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swallower</ent>⟦br⟧
